column168: THE DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING DOWN I-59 WHEN ANOTHER DRIVER ALERTED OUR DRIVER BY CB RADIO THAT A LIQUID WAS RUNNING OUT OF THE TRAILER. OUR DRIVER PULLED OVER TO THE SIDE IF I-59 AND FOUND THE LEAKING DRUM. HE TURNED THE DRUM SO THE HOLE WAS AT THE TOP WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO GET A BAG OF SODA ASH OUT FROM HIS SPILL KIT AND PUT IT ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ON THE PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD. THE BIRMINGHAM HAZMAT TEAM OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER AFTER THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED A REMEDITATION COMPANY BY THE NAME OF HEPACO INC. CONDUCTED THE CLEAN UP. CONTAINER WAS STRAPED TO THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND WAS SETTING ON TOP OF A BULLRING IN THE FLOOR OF TRAILER. WE BELIEVE DUE TO THE CONSTRUCTION OF THE HIGHWAY THE BULLRING RUBBED A HOLE IN THE CONTAINER.

DRIVER LOADED IN BURNS HARBOR, IN INSPECTED HIS TANK AND DROVE TO DETROIT, MI AREA.  HE STOPPED EVERY 2 HOURS AND INSPECTED HIS TANK AND TIRES.  HE SPENT THE NIGHT IN THE DETROIT AREA AND THEN INSPECTED HIS EQUIPMENT THE NEXT MORNING, THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF A LEAK AT THAT TIME.  HE DROVE TO THE PLANT AND WENT TO WEIGH HIS TRUCK.  WHEN GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK HE SMELLED STYRENE MONOMER AND CHECKED HIS TANK.  IT WAS LEAKING ABOUT ONE DROP EVERY 7 SECONDS. HE WAS INSTRUCTED BY THE UNLOADERS TO AIR HIS TANK AND UNLOAD AS SOON AS POSSIBLE.  WHEN HE APPLIED AIR THE LEAK INCREASED.  HE WAS TOLD TO STOP THE PROCESS AND RELEASE THE AIR PRESSURE.  911 CALLED AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND PLACED A PLASTIC POOL UNDER THE TANK.  THE TANK WAS THEN UNLOADED APPROXIMATELY 3 TO 5 GALLONS WERE LOST AND BASF CLEANED UP THE SPILL.

ON DEC 1 99 WE WERE UNLOADING AN AIR TRANSPORT CONTAINER IN OUR WAREHOUSE LOCATION AT EMERY WORLDWIDE AT AUSTIN BERGSTROM INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT. IN THE PROCESS ON UNLOADING THE PN CONTAINER WE DISCOVERED THAT WE APPEARED TO BE WATER IN THE CENTER OF THE CONTAINER.  WE BEGAN TO REMOVE ALL CARGO FROM THE CONTAINER BUT THEN NOTICED IT WAS NOT WATER OR RAIN.  IT WAS LEAKING SLOWLY FROM THE END OF A PLASTIC JERRICAN CONTAINING CORROSIVE HAZMAT LIQUID.  WE CONTACTED THE ABIA FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT INSTRUCTED US TO EVACUATE THE BUILDING WHILE THE AFD HAZMAT TEAM CONTAINED THE SPILL. WE WERE EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR AND 20 MINUTES TOTAL.  ONCE THE AFD HAZMAT TEAM CONTAINED THE INITIAL SPILL, THEY CORDONED OFF THE AREA AND ALLOWED US TO RETURN TO THE BUILDING.  WE THEN CONTACTED A SPILL CLEAN UP TEAM THROUGH THE SPILL CENTER.  THE TEAM (BOOTS AND COOTS SPECIAL SERVICES) NEUTRALIZED THE CONTAINER, THE CARGO NETS THAT SECURED THE CONTAINER, AND THE OTHER TWO SHIPMENTS THAT WERE CONTAMINAED BY THE CORROSIVE LIQUID.  THE AFD HAZMAT TEAM ALSO CHECKED THE AIRCFRAFT (CONTINER WAS LOCATED IN POSITION 1 IN THE AIRCRAFT) BUT FOUND NO SIGN OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  BOOTS AND COOTS LEFT THE CONTAINER OF NEUTRALIZED SPILL MATERIAL AT EMERY'S WAREHOUSE IN THE HAZMAT AREA UNTIL DISPOSITION COULD BE DETERMINED FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: THE TRACTOR-TRAILER LEFT THE ROADWAY AT APPROXIMATELY 12:01 AM ON 12-03-99, THE TRACTOR-TRAILER ROLLED OVER. THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH ARGON, REFRIGERATE LIQUID, WHICH IS A NON-FLAMMABLE, NO-HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE. THE ROLL OVER CAUSED A LIQUID VAPOR RELEASE OF PRODUCT OUT OF THE TRAILER VENT STACK. THIS WAS DUE TO THE TRAILER BEING ON ITS SIDE, PUTTING LIQUID DIRECTLY INTO THE VENT SYSTEM. APPROXIMATELY 200,000 CU FT. OF PRODUCT LOST TO THE ATMOSPHERE, THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED BY TRANSFERRING TO ANOTHER TRAILER. A MINOR SPILL OF DIESEL FUEL AND MOTOR OIL WAS PROMPTLY CLEANED UP BY FERGUSON & HARBOUR CO, WHICH IS A HAZARDOUS RESPONSE CO. THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED NORTH OF THE 257 MILE MARKER ON I-55. THE TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT WAS NORTH BOUND BOTH DRIVERS WERE TAKEN BY AMBULANCE TO THE ELVIS PRESLEY TRAUMA CENTER IN MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE. BOTH DRIVERS SUSTAINED MULTIPLE CUTS & CONTUSIONS TO THE BODY. INFORMATION ON THIS ACCIDENT WAS SENT TO ALL OF OUR TERMINALS TO BE DISCUSSED IN DETAIL.

column168: MISSISSIPPI TRANSPORT WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND AND A PASSENGER VAN WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND.  THE PASSENGER MADE A LEFT TURN STRIKING OUR UNIT. THE UNIT OVERTURNED IN THE DITCH AND ON COMMERCIAL PROPERTY.  SULFUR BEGAN LEAKING FROM TOP OF CARGO TANK IN THE DOME HATCH AREA.  SIOUX HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO SCENE AND SECURED THE SPILL SITE. SITE WAS CLEANED ON 12/03/1999. COMPANY POLICY IS TO REVIEW THE ACCIDENT INFORMATION AND MAKE APPROPRIATE CHANGES WHERE NECESSARY.  NO RECOMMENDATIONS FOR CHANGES IN PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN MADE AS OF THIS DATE.

column168: DURING THE TRUCK TO TRUCK TRASFER OF MATERIAL AT OUR YARD ON DECEMBER 10, 1999, A 95- GALLON 1H2 CONTAINER WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING FROM A PINHOLE LEAK. THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED, AN OUR 40HOUR TRAINED RESPONSE TEAM ENTERED THE TRAILER ON EPA LEVEL B TO CONTAIN INNER APPROXIMATELY OVERPACK. ALL LIQUIDS WERE CONTAINED DURING THE OVERPACKING OPERATION. ALL SOLIDIFIED LIQUIDS AND CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED FOR DISPOSAL. (SEE ATTACHED MANIFEST #98520473). THE OVERPACKED DRUM WAS DELIVERED TO THE INTENDED TSDF ON MONDAY, DECEMBER 13.

A SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE DROPPED A 16 GALLON DRUM WHILE UNLOADING IT FROM HIS VEHICLE.  THE LID OF THE DRUM POPPED OFF WHEN IT STRUCK THE GROUND ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF WASTE TO SPILL INTO SECONDARY CONTAINER.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: PERSONNEL IN CSXT YARD IN FLINT, MICHIGAN NOTICED AN ODOR IN THE YARD.  A CSXT CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND FOUND UTLX803578, A RESIDUE TANK CAR OF LIQUID PETROLEUM GAS, WEEPING VAPOR FROM THE RELIEF VALVE AND FROM A LOOSE PLUG IN THE B END LIQUID VALVE.  THE CONTRACTOR TIGHTENED THE PLUG AND ADJUSTED THE RELIEF VALVE, STOPPING BOTH LEAKS.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT.

WHILE LOADING HIS VEHICLE A 55 GALLON DRUM FELL OFF THE PALLET HITTING THE GROUND, CAUSING THE LID TO POP OFF SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  THE DRIVER ABSORBED AND RECOVERED THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM.

column42: ETHANOL OR ETHYL ALCOHOL OR ETHANOL SOLUTIONS OR ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS
column168: A CSX TRANSPORTATION MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT INSPECTOR OBSERVED A CONTINUOUS DRIP LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP OF TANK CAR GATX 93367.  THE CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (TOBOV).  THE LEAK WAS ESTIMATED AT 1 GALLON EVERY HOUR.  THE PRODUCT SHIPPER AND THE CARRIER WORKED TOGETHER TO SECURE THE CAR. THE TOBOV WAS TURNED TWO REVOLUTIONS TO TIGHTEN, THE VALVE PACKING WAS CHECKED AND THE PACKING NUT TIGHTENED.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAPS WERE ALSO TIGHTENED.  THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED.

A CSX TRANSPORTATION MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT INSPECTOR OBSERVED A PIN HOLE SIZE LEAK IN THE TANK CAR GATX 29181.  THE HOLE WAS LOCATED AT "B" END SADDLE AT THE WELD TO THE TANK BODY.  THE LEAK WAS ESTIMATED AT 1 QUART EVERY 10 MINUTES.  THE PRODUCT SHIPPER AND THE CARRIER WORKED TOGETHER TO OFF LOAD THE CAR INTO TANK TRUCKS.

column168: CSXT TRAIN CREW J72007 DISCOVERED A LOADED TAN CAR OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID, RCRX 1067, LEAKING IN HENDERSON, KENTUCKY.  THE CREW STOPPED THEIR TRAIN AND LOCAL EMERGENCY AUTHORITIES RESPONDED. THE HENDERSON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM DETERMINED THAT A RUPTURE DISC HAD BLOWN.  THE CONSIGNEE, PB & S CHEMICAL, RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE DISC.  THE CAR WAS SHIPPED TO THE CUSTOMER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: AT 1830 A DRIVER  NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM A TRAILER #313-8010. THE DRIVER REPORTED THE SMELL TO MYSELF ROBERT THOMPSON DOCK SUPERVISOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF PAPER WORK AND EMERGENCY HAZMAT GUIDE I SECURED AND ISOLATED CYLINDER ONTO TRAILER #313-8010 CALLED SHIPPER'S EMERGENCY NUMBER.  THEY SENT A COMPANY REP OUT TO INDIANAPOLIS XIN DOCK TO REPAIR AND OR CONTAIN SHIPMENT.  THEY ARRIVED APPROXIMATELY 19:35 AND REPAIRED CYLINDER.  LEAK WAS STOPPED AND PROCEEDED TO SEND SHIPMENT TO CONSIGNEE.  BEFORE SHIPMENT DEPARTED XIN DOCK WE NOTICED THE SAME ODOR ONCE AGAIN ISOLATED SHIPMENT CALLED SHIPPER.  THEY SENT A REP OUT AGAIN CONTAINED CYLINDER AND TRANSPORTED IT BACK TO THEIR DOCK.

WHILE UNLOADING A LEAKING 300 GALLON TOTE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE TOTE TANK WAS LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE CAP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS. THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 30 GALLON FIBER DRUM. THE FIBER DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE TOTE WAS PATCHED AND WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPERS DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

WHILE UNLOADING A DAMAGED FIVE GALLON PAIL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE PAIL WAS DAMAGED BY HEAVY TOPFREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP LEVEL C. ABSORBENT MATERIALS USED TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT. THE DAMAGED PAIL REMAINING PRODUCT, ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PACED INTO A SEVEN GALLON FIBER DRUM. THE FIBER DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: WHILE UNLOADING A DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED A DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING 3,1 GALLON CONTAINERS. APPARENTLY WHILE LOADING THE TRAILER A ONE GALLON CONTAINER WAS PUNCTURED. APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OF A GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT RELEASED. THE CARTON WAS LOCATED IN THE QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED PAPER TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS AND THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE CONTAINERS WERE REPACKED AND FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

WHILE UNLOADING A DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED A 75 GALLON TOTE LEAKING. APPARENTLY A LOOSE VALVE CAUSED APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT TO RELEASE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED ABSORBENT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 14 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM AND A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH OF THE DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TOTE WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

WHILE UNLOADING A DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED A WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR 1/2 GALLON CONTAINERS. AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A 1/2 GALLON CONTAINER WAS DAMAGED BY A LOOSE LID CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 20 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT TO RELEASE. THE TERMINAL HAXMAT USED LEVEL B TO PERFORM CLEAN UP. THE HAXMAT TEAM TIGHTENED THE VALVE AND CLEANED OFF THE AFFECTED CONTAINERS. THE CARTON AND THE CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO A SMALL FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

TERMINAL PERSONNEL NOTICED AN ODOR AFTER OPENING TRAILER DOORS. HAZMAT IN QUESTION WAS PACKAGE IN FOUR 55 GALLON STEEL BUNGTOP DRUMS IN THE NOSE ON A SKID WITH NO TOP FREIGHT. HAZMAT PERSONNEL USED A DUST MASK TO INVESTIGATE AND FOUND THAT ONE DRUM WHICH HAS A SMALL DENT PUNCTURE FROM UNKNOWN REASON HAS RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF FREE PRODUCT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR HMHTTC RESPONDED TO PERFORM ADDITIONAL CLEAN UP. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: WHILE UNLOADING A LEAKING 33 GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF THE FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS LEAKING DUE TO PACKAGING FAILURE CAUSED BY TIGHT SHRINK WRAP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS REMAINING PRODUCT ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON FIBER DRUM. THE FIBER DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT AWAITING SHIPPERS DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

WHILE UNLOADING ONE DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING 12 16 OUNCE BOTTLES WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE BOTTLES WAS DAMAGED RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 16 OUNCES. THE REMAINING 11 CONTAINERS WERE AFFECTED BY THE FREE PRODUCT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WET CARTON AND 12 16 OUNCE BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO ONE 35 GALLON OVERPACK DRUM. THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. ONE EMPLOYEE COAT WAS EXPOSED TO THE FREE PRODUCT. EMPLOYEE CHANGED CLOTHES WASHED AND WENT BACK TO MEDICAL TREATMENT WAS NOT SOUGHT. A MEDICAL REPORT WAS FILLED OUT.

WHILE UNLOADING ONE 4000 POUND STAINLESS STEEL TOTE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. APPARENTLY 2 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE TOTE HAD A SLOW CONTINUOUS LEAK. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL AND CONTAINED THE FREE PRODUCT WITH ABSORBENT BOOMS. THE TOTE WAS REPAIRED WITH NEW DOUGH. THE LEAKING TOTE WAS ISOLATED IN THE TRAILER AND BOOMS WERE PLACED AROUND THE LEAKING TOTE. AFTER THE TRANSFER IS COMPLETE, THE NEW CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE THREE OTHER TOTES WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNOADING TRAILER A DOCK WORKER NOTICED A 55 GALLON DRUM OF PRODUCT WAS LEAKING. APPARENTLY PACKAGING FAILURE CAUSED 1 PINT OF PRODUCT TO RELEASE. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE VEHICLE WAS SOUTHBOUND ON ROUTE 654 WHICH IS A 2 LANE ROAD MARKED BY DOUBLE SOLID LINES.  AS A NORTHBOUND VEHICLE APPROACHED, THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STAY TO THE RIGHT TO ALLOW CLEARANCE BETWEEN THE 2 VEHICLES. IN DOING SO, THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE DROPPED OFF OF THE PAVEMENT.  AT THIS LOCATION THERE IS NO SHOULDER.  THE DRIVER OVER CORRECTED IN PULLING BACK INTO THE PAVEMENT FORCING THE TRUCK TO TURN OVER ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE.  THE TRUCK CONTINUED TO ROLL OVER AND STRUCK A TREE.  WE BELIVE THIS IMPACT JARRED THE REAR VALVE ON THE TRUCK ALLOWING A SMALL BUT UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF PROPANE TO LEAK.  THE VALVE WAS RESECURED.  APPROX 1,100 GALLONS OF PROPANE WAS SUBSEQUENTLY BURNED OFF OF THE TRUCK IN A CONTROLLED BURN TO EMPTY THE VESSEL PRIOR TO REMOVING IT FROM THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT. PROPERTY DAMAGED OTHER THAN THE TRUCK WAS AN ELM TREE AND A SECTION OF LANDSCAPE TIMBERS.  IN OUR CONTINUING SAFETY MEETINGS ALL DRIVERS WILL BE TRAINED IN THE RECOGNITION OF HIGHWAY HAZARDS AS WELL AS IN OVER REACTING TO UNFORESEEN CIRCUMSTANCES.

column168: AARON OIL COMPANY WAS OPERATING A SINGLE COMPARTMENT SMOOTH BORE TANKER TRAILER PULLED BY AOC TRUCK NO 44 BY A HIGHLY TRAINED FULLY QUALIFIED CDL. CLASS A DRIVER WITH A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ENDORSEMENT. TRAILER WAS LOADED AT LOADING DESTINATION FULL INSPECTION PRIOR TO AND AFTER LOADING AS TRAINED UNDER HM 126 F AND HM 183. NO PROBLEMS WERE IDENTIFIED. THE DOME LID WAS COMING TO A STOP ON SLOW DOWN 5000 WEST BANK EXPRESSWAY OR US 90 AT LA HWY 45 THE MOUNTING PLATFORM FOR THE DOME LID CAME UNSECURED FROM THE TANKER SPILLING OIL ON THE ROADWAY. IT IS BELIEVED THAT DURING THE LAST CONFINED SPACE ENTRY TO CLEAN THE TANKER THE MOUNTING PLATFORM THAT SECURES THE DOME LID TO THE TRAILER WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED ON THE NUT AND BOLT THAT HOLDS THE RING MAY HAVE VIBRATED ON WORKED A LOOSE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP UNDER STATE AND LOCAL SUPERVISION. ADDITIONAL PROCEDURES WILL BE WRITTEN TO ADDRESS THIS ISSUE.

DRIVER OF #3351, A 3 COMPARTMENT STAINLESS STEEL TRAILER, HAD FINISHED WITH A 2300 GALLON DELIVERY OF A NATURAL GAS PURIFYING AGENT AT A NATURAL GAS FIELD 35 MILES SOUTH OF MOAB, UT.  HE WAS ON THE ROAD LEAVING THE GAS FIELD WHEN HE STOPPED.  THE DRIVER NOTICED A DUST CAP LOOSE ON THE COMPARTMENT HE HAD JUST UNLOADED SO HE ATTEMPTED TO PUT IT BACK ON.  WHILE PUTTING THE DUST CAP THE DRIVER BUMPED A BLEEDER VALVE HE BUMPED IT OPEN FROM THE CLOSED POSITION. THE DRIVER PANICKED AND RAN TO HIS TRACTOR. BEFORE THE COMPARTMENT DRAINED OUT THE DRIVER HAD MOVED HIS TRUCK APPROXIMATELY 1/16 OF A MILE.  NO ONE KNOWS FOR SURE HOW MUCH WAS RELEASED BUT IT IS ESTIMATED TO BE AT LEAST 100 GALLONS.  THE CUSTOMER FOUND THE RELEASED PRODUCT THE NEXT DAY WHILE DRIVING DOWN THE ROAD.  NO ITEM ON THE TRAILER FAILED TO PERFORM.  DRIVER FAILED AND PANICKED.

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT WHERE IT HIT A GUARD RAIL WHILE TRAVELING APPROX. 60 MPH.  AS A RESULT OF STRIKING THE GUARD RAIL, THE MOUNTING BRACKETS FOR THE TANK BROKE LOOSE, CAUSING THE TANK TO COME OFF THE BED AND LAND ON THE ROAD.  UPON STRIKING THE ROAD, THE TANK RUPTURED, SPILLING THE CONTENTS ONTO THE ROAD. CONTAMINANT CONTROL INC (438 ROBESON ST. FAYETTEVILLE, NC 28361) WAS CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  THE MATERIAL WAS SUBSEQUENTLY SHIPPED TO ENVIROCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC 1005 INVESTMENT BLVD APEX NC 27502, FOR INCINERATION.  THE TRUCK WAS RETURNED TO THE OLIN OFFICE, CLEANED AND STORED.

THE CONE SOLVENT TANKER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON US 231 WHEN A DRIVER FOR UNIQUE CAR CARE & LIMO BACKED INTO ONCOMING TRAFFIC. column168: THE MEDFORD HAZMAT RESPONSE AGENCY NOTIFIED OUR MEDFORD OFFICE THAT A TANK CAR ON OUR TRAIN IN MEDFORD WAS LEAKING.  UPON INSPECTION BY OUR SUPT. OF OPERATIONS, THE CAR WAS DETERMINED TO BE LEAKING FROM ITS BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE GASKET AT A RATE OF APPROX.  1 GAL/MIN.  THE CAR WAS THEN SET OUT OF THE TRAIN IN OUR MEDFORD RAIL YARD AND ISOLATED, PENDING ARRIVAL OF THE OREGON EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND MEDFORD FIRE DEPT.  AT APPROX. 0945 THESE TWO AGENCIES WERE ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE VALVE SO THAT THE LEAK WAS REDUCED TO ABOUT 1 GAL/HR., AND A 5 GAL BUCKET WAS ATTACHED TO THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR TO CATCH THE SPILL.  THE MEDFORD FIRE DEPT. THEN GAVE PERMISSION FOR THE RAILROAD TO MOVE THE CAR TO GEORGIA PACIFIC AT WHITE CITY (APPROX. 13 MILES) FOR UNLOADING.

THE FUEL HOSE ATTACHED TO TANKER-TRAILER CAME UNCOUPLED FROM THE FUEL VALVE ON TRAILER AND SPILLED APPROXIMATELY.  100-200 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL OIL ONTO DIRT ROADWAY NEAR THE FUEL CONTAINMENT STATION. THE AREA CONTAMINATED WAS APPROXIMATELY 20' WIDE BY 100' OF GROUND SOIL IN DRAINAGE DITCH. BLAKE ANDUSEN OF IES ENERGY PLANT, IMMEDIATELY DUMPED 100 TONS OF BOTTOM ASH ONTO FUEL SPILL AREA. MR ANDUSEN CONTACTED SHINN TRUCKING TO HAUL CONTAMINATED BUTTON ASH AND GROUND SOIL TO WAPELLO COUNTY LANDFILL FOR DISPOSAL. ALL CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES FOR THE FUEL SPILL WERE COMPLETED 12/10/1999

column168: I RECEIVED A PAGE AT 2216 FROM THE NYCA FEDEX FACILITY.  I IMMEDIATELY CALLED THEM BACK AND SPOKE WITH MARIA COLLADO (A STATION MANAGER).  A FEDEX ENVELOPE ACCEPTED AT THE NYCE FACILITY (BUSINESS SERVICE CENTER) THAT HAD BEEN BROUGHT WITH OTHER FREIGHT TO THE NYCA STATION HAD IGNITED AND GONE OUT AT SOME POINT (THE IGNITION WENT UNNOTICED).  THIS ENVELOPE WAS IN A DOCUMENT BAG AND THE ODOR FROM THE BAG WAS BROUGHT TO THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST'S ATTENTION. WHEN MARIA FOUND THE SUSPICIOUS PACKAGE, SHE OBSERVED THAT THE ENVELOPE HAD BEEN CYLINDER.  AT THIS POINT, NOT KNOWING WHAT THE CYLINDER WAS, MARIA CLEARED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED FEDEX SECURITY AND THE LOCAL POLICE.  AFTER FEDEX SECURITY ARRIVED, THE POLICE CAME AND NOTIFIED THE BOMB SQUAD AFTER BEING BRIEFED ABOUT THE EVENTS. THE BUILDING WAS EVACUATED FROM 1925-2020. THE POLICE (OFFICER RAPISARDA) CONFISCATED THE PACKAGE AND THE STATION SORT OPERATIONS BEGAN AS SOON AS THE BUIDING WAS OCCUPIED AGAIN.  THIS PACKAGE WAS LATER FOUND TO BE A BOX OF MATCHES WITH A SPECIAL CYLINDRICAL MATCH HOLDER IN A FIBRE TUBE.  I NOTIFIED THE FAA DUTY AGENT AT 2310 AND FOLLOWED UP THE NEXT DAY BY CALLING FAA AGENT THOMAS CARTER.  AS STATED EARLIER, THE PACKAGE IS IN POLICE CUSTODY UNTIL IT IS CLEARED FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

WHEN THE FREIGHT WAS OFFLOADED AT THE GREAT FALLS FEDEX RAMP, THE PKG WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE RAMP'S SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CLEANED UP THE SPILL PER FEDEX POLICY AND PROCEDURE.  THE RECIPIENT WAS CONTACTED AND THEY DID WANT THIS PACKAGE AFTER THE CLEANUP AND PACKAGE PREPARATION WAS COMPLETE.

TANK CAR ISOLATED, AND THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED. GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL OF DEER PARK, TEXAS RESPONDED FOR A SITE ASSESSMENT.  GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL DETERMINED THAT NO CLEAN UP WAS REQUIRED.  THE CYLINDER WAS SECURED AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

column168: DOCK MAN DISCOVERED DAMAGED CARTON HILE UNLOADING FREIGHT OFF THE INBOUND TRAILER.  THE FREIGHT LOADER AT THE PREVIOUS TERMINAL HAD LOADED A SKID OF FREIGHT ON TOP OF THE CARTONS OF CORROSIVE LIQUID. APPARENTLY, DURING TRANSIT, THE WEIGHT OF THE SKID OF FREIGHT ON TOP OF THE CARTONS OF CORROSIVE LIQUID CRUSHED ONE OF THE CARTONS WITH THE EXTERNAL PRESSURE BURSTING ONE OF THE BAGS INSIDE THE CARTON. FREIGHT LOADERS MUST USE GOOD JUDGMENT TP PREVENT DAMAGE HEN LOADING FREIGHT TO RIDE ON TRAILERS.

BIGX 1009, LD ARGON, REPORTED VENTING VAPORS FROM THE TOP CONTINUOUSLY AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN DETROIT, MI.  THE TRAINMASTER INSPECTED THE CAR & FOUND FROST ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THRU CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER SENT SOMEONE OUT OF CHICAGO TO CHECK THE CAR.  THE SERVICE TECHIAN CHECKED THE CAR % FOUND THE VACUUM ON THE CAR WAS 500 MICRONS.  CARS ARE NORMALLY SHIPPED WITH A VACUUM OF 300 MICRONS.  CAR VENTING MORE ACCOUNT VACUUM IS A LITTLE LO BUT VENTING IS CONSIDERED TO BE A NORMAL PROCESS.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A WHITE POWDER WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. MSDS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. THE DAMAGED BAG OF PRODUCT, WITH THE REMAINDER OF UNRELEASED PRODUCT, WAS PLACED INTO A 30 GALLON FIBER DRUM.  ALL 3 DRUMS WILL BE HELD, AWAITING DISPOSITION. WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED, FIVE-GALLON PAILS WERE DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 1/2/ GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND AFFECTED FOUR, FIFTEEN POUND BAGS OF THE SAME PRODUCT AS WELL AS ONE BOX OF FURNITURE.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAILS WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND PAPER TOWELS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FOUR AFFECTED FIFTEEN POUND BAGS AND TWO DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE WET CARDBOARD WAS PLACED INTO A FIVE-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE AFFECTED BOX OF FURNITURE WAS REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, DAMPNESS WAS OBSERVED ON THE BOTTOM OF A SHIPPING CARTON CONTAINING FOUR 1 GALLON PLASTIC JUGS OF PRODUCT. CLEAN UP MATERIALS ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A 10 GALLON AND A 30 GALLON LINED FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS.  THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED ON THE AFFECTED JUG AND THE FOUR JUGS RE-BOXED FOR SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT.  AN MSDS ACCOMPANIED THE SHIPMENT.

THE DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED BAG WAS REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

WHILE UNLOADING, A WET CARTON CONTAINING SIX, ON-GALLON PAILS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS.   THE DAMAGED PAIL, WET CARTON, ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 10-GALLON FIBER DRUM.  THE FIBER DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE UNAFFECTED CANS WERE REPACKAGED, AND WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, THREE WET CARTONS CONTAINING 12, 32-OUNCE BOTTLES EACH WERE DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT 12 OF THE BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED, AND 24 BOTTLES WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY 32 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE BOTTLES WERE CRUSHED BY HEAVY TOPFREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C.  ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 30-GALLON FIBER DRUM.  THE DAMAGED BOTTLES AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 20-GALLON PLASTIC DRUM. THE WET CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO A SEPARATE 20-GALLON PLASTIC DRUM.  THE PLASTIC DRUMS AND THE FIBER DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE UNAFFECTED BOTTLES WERE REPACKAGED, AND WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, A DAMAGED 55 GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK.  APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. THE DAMAGED DRUM AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON OVERPACK DRUM.  THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPERS DISPOSITION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, A 55 GALLON DRUM WAS NOTICED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WITH A LOOSE BUNG CAP.  APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE TERMINAL HAZ MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL B PROTECTION.  THE DAMAGED DRUM AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 95 GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM.  THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING RECEIPT OF TH SHIPPER'S DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS.  THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  ONE EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED AND RETURNED TO WORK AFTER EVALUATION AT THE TERMINAL EMERGENCY CARE STATION.  STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY REPORTING WAS COMPLETED.  AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  LEONA BOWSER WE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT

SHIPMENT WAS NOTED DAMAGED ON ARRIVAL AT ELKO.  DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO DELIVER THE DRUM TO THE CONSIGNEE. BUT CONSIGNEE, BUT CONSIGNEE REFUSED.  STATED THAT DUE TO DAMAGE THE DRUM PRODUCT WAS CONTAMINATED AND COULD NOT BE USED.  SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO DOCK AND PLACED ON A PALLET OUTSIDE OF  TERMINAL BUILDING.  FLOOR DAY WAS USED TO ABSORB THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND A RECOVERY DRUM WAS REQUESTED FROM SLC, SHIPPER WAS TO ADVISE DISPOSITION.  DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM AND IS SETTING ON ELK DOCK.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE WAS EASTBOUND ON I-285 APPROACHING THE SPLIT WITH I -75N; DRIVER WAS IN THE RIGHT TRAVEL LANE.  VEHICLE ENTERED THEC URVE, THE TANKER ROLLED OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE WHICH CAUSED THE TRACTOR TO ROLL OVER AS WELL.  AT THIS POINT, THE TRACTOR SEPARATED.  TANKER RUPTURED UPON CONTACT WITH THE GROUND;HERITAGE TRANSPORT WILL CONDUCT SAFETY TRAINING WHICH CONCENTRATES ON SPEED, NIGHT DRIVING, SHIFTING LOADS AND GENERAL DRIVING SAFETY.

RAILROAD TANK CAR ACFX 83630, EMPTY WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BEING SWITCHED AT KC'S KANSAS CITY, MO.  TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO REMOTE TRACK AND A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER HE LEAK.

MECHANICAL PERSONNEL OBSERVED VAPORS EMMITTING FROM TH ETOP OF TANK CAR UTLX 99060 WHILE IT WAS WITHIN THE BOUREGARD YARD.  THE PACKING NUT ON THE DIP TUBE WAS  LOOSE ALLOWING THE VAPORS TO ESCAPE. SHIPPER NOTIFIED A LOCAL HAZMAT CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR, THE NUT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  TANK CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 1200 HOURS.

THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT WHILE IN THE BUILDING WAREHOUSE.  SOME DETAILS WEREN'T NOTED AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL SO THEY ARE NOT AVAILABLE FOR THIS REPORT.  THE CONSIGNEE TOOK POSSESSION OF THE DAMAGED FREIGHT.

THIS PLASTIC DRUM WAS DAMAGED DURING THE OUTBOUND SORT OPERATIONS. THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CLEANED UP THE SPILL PER FEDEX POLICY. A MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND WAS FAXED TO THE FEDEX STATION.  THE FLASHPOINT WAS LISTED AS 129 DEGREES FARENHEIT, SO THIS FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INVESTIGATION.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED COMING FROM THE PACKAGING.  THE BOX WAS NOT LABELED OR MARKED AS TO DECLARE IT CONTAINED ANY DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCTS, NOR WAS THERE ANY PAPERWORK TO DECLARE THIS SHIPMENT AS DANGEROUS GOODS.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS, IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE LIQUID HAD LEAKED AROUND THE CLOSURES OF THE INNER CANS.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND ATTEMPTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO PROVIDE A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ASSOCIATED WITH THE PRODUCT.  THE MSDS WAS  RECEIVED AND IT STATED THE SHIPMENT HAD FLASH POINT OF 104 DEGREES Fahrenheit.  I  CONTACTED AGENT NETTLES OF THE BWI/CASFU AND LATER SPOKE TO DENNIS HARVELL HO INVESTIGATED THE INCIDENT.  PACKAGE WAS RELEASED AND PICKED UP BY THE SHIPPER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: A PROTRUDING NAIL FROM A PALLET PUNCTURED THE DRUM, RESULTING IN THE SPILL.  THE DISTRIBUTION CENTER WAS INFORMED OF THE ISSUE, SO THAT CORRECTIVE MEASURES WILL BE IMPLEMENTED.  THE PRODUCT WAS REMEDIATED BY BOOTS & COOTS FOR INCINERATION.

WHILE PREPARING TO LOAD FREIGHT INTO CONTAINER FOR AIRCRAFT, THE BOX WAS ACCIDENTALLY DAMAGED WITH FORKLIFT/DRIVER.  PACKAGING MATERIAL ABSORBED LEAKAGE FROM 1 GLASS BOTTLE.  REMAINING 4 BOTTLES WERE DISPOSED OF AS HAZ WASTE, WITH CORRECT MIA WASTESTREAM - WASTE PAINT, HAZARDOUS.  PACKAGING MATERIAL DRIED AND WAS DISPOSED IN SOLID TRASH NO DELAYS RESULTED FROM INCIDENT.  LOCAL FAA WAS NOTIFIED.  MANIFEST #00011 LINE 11A (1 GAL)

WHILE AT UNLOADING DOCK, AN EMPLOYEE NOTICED THE CAN TO BE LEAKING FROM THE HANDLE AT THE TOP OF THE CAN.  THE SUBSTANCE THAT LEAKED OUT SEALED THE OPENING AND PREVENTED FURTHER LEAKAGE FROM OCCURRING.

column168: A SYNCOR DRIVER IN A NON-COMMERCIAL VEHICLE COLLIDED WITH ANOTHER VEHICLE AT AN INTERSECTION. DIESEL FUEL EMANATED FROM THE NON-SYNCOR VEHICLE FUEL TANKS, WHICH WAS LATER CLEANED UP BY A COMPANY SUGGESTED BY THE EPA.  ELEVEN OUT OF THE TWELVE AMMO CANS ORIGINALLY IN THE SYNCOR VEHICLE WERE THROWN FROM THE VEHICLE DURING THE ACCIDENT.  ONE OF THE TWELVE AMMO CANS WAS LABELED "RADIOACTIVE WHITE I."  THE REMAINING CANS WERE CONSIDERED TO BE EXCEPTED PACKAGES, LIMITED QUANTITY, AND WERE NOT REQUIRED TO BE LABELED.  ALL AMMO CANS WERE RETRIEVED.  BOTH ROADS WERE CLOSED FOR GREATER THAN ONE HOUR, THEREFORE A REPORT WAS PHONED INTO THE DOT RESPONSE NUMBER.  THE ROADS, HOWEVER, ARE NOT MAJOR THOROUGHFARES, THEREFORE REPORTING WAS NOT REQUIRED.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING TOTE TANK OFF OF TRAILER.  TRAILER WAS HIGHER THAN DOCK, RAISED TOTE UP ABOUT 1 FT TO GET IT OUT OF TRAILER.  WHEN EMPLOYEE GOT THE TOTE OUT OF THE TRAILER DIDN'T LOWER IT BACK TO GROUND BEFORE HE MADE HIS TURN TO STABILIZE TOTE.  CHEMICAL STARTED TO SPLASH INSIDE AND FLIPPED THE TOTE OVER.  THE TOP CAP OF THE TOTE WASN'T SEALED PROPERLY SO IT BURST OPEN AND CHEMICAL FLOWED ONTO DOCK.  CHEMICAL WAS CONTAINED ON DOCK BY OIL DSP.  PROPER HANDLING TECHNIQUES OF TOTES AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HAS BEEN RE-TAUGHT.  IF THE TOTE WOULD HAVE HAD FORKLIFT BRACES ON IT LIKE MOOT TOTE DO, THIS WOULDN'T HAVE HAPPENED.  SHIPPER NEEDS TO USE DIFFERENT TOTE.

A CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE, INC. ("CHESI") VAN TRAILER CONTAINING NINETY (90) DRUMS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM BAYER CORPORATION LOCATED AT 8500 WEST BAY ROAD IN BAYTOWN, TX TO CLEAN HARBORS ENV. SERVICES, INC LOCATED AT 5 MILES SOUTH OF KIMBALL ON HIGHWAY 71 IN KIMBALL, NE.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP THE DRIVER PARKED HIS VEHICLE AT THE ROADSIDE REST AREA LOCATED ON I-278 NORTH IN IOWA PARK, TEXAS IN ORDER TO OBTAIN REST.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1:55 AM ON DECEMBER 25, 1999, TH DRIVER WAS AWAKENED BY THE SOUND IF A DRUM RUPTURING IN THE WASTE HAULING PORTION OF THE VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND MADE SEVERAL NOTIFICATIONS.  HE CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER, THE TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE MANAGER, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THE LOCAL POLICE DEPARTMENT.  THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, AND THE TEXAS DOT, AND THE SHIPPER WERE ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY, GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. ("GARNER") WAS CONTRACTED AND DISPATCHED TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  A REVIEW OF THE SITUATION DETERMINED THAT ONE DRUM HAD RUPTURED AND THREE MORE WERE BULGING FROM INTERNAL PRESSURE.  UTILIZING A REMOTE CONTROL APPARATUS, PERSONNEL RELIEVED THE EXCESS PRESSURE IN THE THREE BULGING DRUMS AND PLACED THE DRUMS INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUMS FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  ALL REMAINING CONTAINERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE.  THE MATERIAL RELEASED FROM THE ONE RUPTURED DRUM  WAS PACKAGED IT INTO SUITABLE DRUMS FOR SHIPMENT.  A DECONTAMINATION ON ALL OF THE CONTAMINATED SURFACES INCLUDING THE TRAILER, THE UNDAMAGED DRUMS, AND THE PAVED PARKING AREA NEAR THE TRAILER WAS PERFORMED.  THE SPILL DECONTAMINATION DEBRIS WAS ALSO CONTAINERIZED FOR THE SHIPMENT. SUBSEQUENT TO THE IMMEDIATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIVITY THE REMAINING EIGHTY-NINE (89) DRUMS ALONG WITH THE FIVE (5) SPILL CLEANUP DRUMS WERE REDIRECTED BACK TO THE GENERATOR, BAYER CORPORATION IN BAYTOWN, TX FOR FURTHER REVIEW AND ANALYSIS. ENCLOSED PLEASE FIND A PHOTOCOPY OF THE ORIGINAL MANIFEST IDENTIFYING THE TRACKING THE NINETY-FOUR (94) DRUMS BACK TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER, BAYER CORPORATION IN BAYTOWN, TX.

BAX GLOBAL RECEIVED 122 PLASTIC JERRICANS FROM ROHM & HAAS.  THE CONTAINERS WERE PLACED ON TWO SEPARATE WOODEN PALLETS.  THESE PALLETS WERE SHRINK WRAPPED AND THEN DOUBLE STACKED.  WHEN THE PALLETS WERE LOADED THE DRIVER ASKED THE LOADER IF IT WAS CORRECT THAT THE PALLETS HAD BEEN DOUBLE STACKED.  THE DRIVER WAS INFORMED THAT ROHM & HAAS DOUBLE LOADS STACKED FREIGHT IN THIS MANNER, CONSISTENTLY.  EN ROUTE TO THE IAH TERMINAL THE FREIGHT SHIFTED RESULTING IN AN UNKNOWN QUANTITY TO BE RELEASED. WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED THE DRIVE CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR TO INFORM HIM OF THE INCIDENT.  THE SUPERVISOR THEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER. THE SHIPPER SENT IN THEIR 24 HOUR RESPONSE TEAM TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.
2 DOME COVERS WERE CLOSED BUT NOT LOCKED, THIS ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.

column168: AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY THERE WAS A SMALL PUDDLE OF PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR NEAR THE FRONT.  WHEN THE BOTTOM WAS EXAMINED PRODUCT WAS VISIBLE THERE.  COSIGNEE PERSON WIPED THE BOTTOM WITH A RAG BUT COULD FIND NO ACTIVE LEAK.  THEY ACCEPTED THE DRUM AND PROVIDED THE DRIVER EITH MATERIALS TO CLEAN THE TRAILER FLOOR, THEN DISCARDED THE MATERIALS IN THEIR OWN SYSTEM

AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP IT WAS NECESSARY TO BRING SOME DOUBLE STACKED FREIGHT TO THE FLOOR IN ORDER FOR THAT CUSTOMER TO UNLOAD ITS SHIPMENT.  WHEN THEY WERE PLACING IT BACK ON THE VEHICLE, ONE DRUM OF ANOTHER SHIPMENT WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORK LIFT.  DUE TO THE HIGH VISCOSITY OF THE MATERIAL, THE LEAKAGE WAS NOT DISCOVERED UNTIL THE NEXT STOP.  DRIVER SECURED ASSISTANCE TO SET THE DRUM ON ITS HEAD AND CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE.  THE DRUM WAS TAKEN TO A CARRIER FACILITY, OVERPACKED AND HELD FOR THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.

DURING UNLOADING OF DOUBLE STACKED FREIGHT AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP, THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR INADVERTENTLY ALLOWED HIS FORKS TO PROTRUDE THROUGH A PALLET.  THE FORKS CONTACTED AND PIERCED A DRUM AHEAD OF THEM.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED ONTO ITS SIDE; THEN PLACED ON AND SECURED TO A PALLET.  DAMAGED AREA WAS SEALED FOR RETURN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY AND THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS DECONTAMINATED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, FIFTY POUND BAG WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED SOME DUNNAGE.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO PACKAGE FAILURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A BOOM AND A DUSTPAN.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM,.  THE AFFECTED DUNNAGE, BROOM AND DUSTPAN WERE PLACED INTO A SEPARATE FIFTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL THREE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE LOADING, A SOCK WORKER DISCOVERED A 55 GALLON DRUM LEAKING. APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT TO RELEASE.  THE DRUM WAS LOCATED AT THE 75% MARK OF THE TRAILER.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING ABSORBENTS AND BOOMS.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO 2, 55 GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUMS.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A OVERPACK DRUM.  THE THREE DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

WHILE UNLOADING, A DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED A DAMAGED CARTON CONTAINING 4, 1 GALLON CONTAINERS.  APPARENTLY HAZMAT SHIFTED CAUSING A ONE GALLON CONTAINER TO RELEASE APPROXIMATELY A HALF OF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT.  THE CARTON WAS LOCATED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED ABSORBENT TOWELS AND GLOVES TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS, CARTON, GLOVES AND DAMAGED CONTAINER WERE PLACED INTO A 15 GALLON FIBER DRUM.  THE DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

NONE OF THE MATERIAL REACHED ANY DRAINS OR SOIL. column168: DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON MO 49 HIGHWAY.  HE RAN OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY, AND OVERTURNED. AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 A.M. ON WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 8, 1999 OUR DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF FILLING THE 4000 GAL TANK AT BBS LOBSTER CO. WHEN THE POCKET HE WAS PUMPING FROM RAN DRY. HE LEFT THE NOZZLE IN THE TANK AND WENT BACK TO THE TRUCK TO OPEN ANOTHER TANK POCKET. WHEN HE RETURNED, HE REALIZED THE TANK WAS OVERFILLING. HE SHUT THE NOZZLE OFF AND WENT TO THE TRUCK TO GET SOME ABSORBENT PADS TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. HE USED WHAT PADS HE HAD TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND THEN RETURNED TO THE  OFFICE TO GET MORE PADS. HE DID NOT REALIZE THAT THE CONTAINMENT DRAIN VALVE WAS OPEN. WHILE HE WAS AT THE OFFICE, WE RECEIVED A CALL FROM BBS LOBSTER SAYING THAT OIL WAS SPILLING INTO THE WATER. WE IMMEDIATELY SENT SEVERAL PEOPLE DOWN WITH SEVERAL BUNDLES OF ABSORBENT PADS AND OIL BOOMS. WORKING WITH BBS PERSONNEL, WE BOOMED OFF THE AREA NEAR THE POUND AND BEGAN SOAKING UP THE OIL. IT WAS A COOL, WINDY DRY DAY WITH A WIND SPEED OF 15-20 MPH BLOWING OUT OF THE NORTHWEST. THE DIRECTION OF THE WIND WAS SUCH THAT IT CONTAINED MOST TO THE OIL IN A SMALL COVE NEXT TO THE POUND. A SMALL AMOUNT OF OIL WAS CARRIED OUT TO SEA BY THE TIDE. IT IS UNCERTAIN HOW MUCH OIL WAS CARRIED OUT TO SEA AND HOW MUCH REMAINED IN THE COVE. THE TOTAL SPILL WAS ESTIMATED TO BE BETWEEN 50-75 GALLONS. I NOTIFIED THE EPA OFFICE IN BANGOR, MAINE ABOUT THE INCIDENT AND THEY ADVISED ME TO CALL THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. I NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WHILE AT THE SITE AND FILLED OUT A REPORT OVER THE PHONE. THEY INDICATED THAT NO OTHER REPORT WOULD BE NECESSARY, AND THAT THEY WOULD NOTIFY THE COAST GUARD. THE COAST GUARD REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED AT THE SITE THAT AFTERNOON. BY THE TIME THEY ARRIVED THE SPILL HAD  BEEN COMPLETELY CLEANED UP. THEY DID AN INSPECTION OF THE AREA AND WERE SATISFIED THAT WE HAD DONE A THOROUGH JOB OF CLEANING UP THE SPILL.THEY INDICATED THAT SOMEONE FROM THEIR INVESTIGATION DEPARTMENT WOULD VISIT US TO DISCUSS THE INCIDENT AND FILL OUT A REPORT. APPARENTLY THE CONTAINMENT VALVE HAD BEEN RECENTLY REMOVED DURING CONSTRUCTION OF AN ENCLOSURE AROUND THE STORAGE TANK TO ALLOW WATER TO DRAIN OUT. ABSORBENT PADS AND OIL BOOMS WERE DISPOSED OF BY BURNING.

FILE AB9299, SHPR: C S X TRANSPORTATION, AIRWAY BILL #NSR 3927790788 JAX, THIS IS A 5800.1 REPORT ONLY.    ON 12/2/99 A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT ABC AIR, INC, 146 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, RANDY WILLIAMS, TIM HINES AND MIKE COOK RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE GEAR AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  THEY DISCOVERED 2 FIBERBOARD BOXES.  ON E OF THE BOXES SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER BOX.  THE BOX THAT LEAKED WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS FOLLOWS: THE TOP OF THE BOX HAD AN ADDRESS LABEL.  SIDE 1 OF THE BOX HAD: UN, 4G/V8/8/97 USA/+BOO307 AND THE WORDS (ACCEPTABLE FOR AIR, SEA AND GROUND.  SIDE 3 OF THE BOX HAD: 1 X 1 U.S. QUART, F STYLE, DIESEL FUEL LTD WTY., NA 1983 AND A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL. SIDE 2 AND 4 OF THE BOX HAD ORIENTATION ARROWS ONLY.  THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD UN401.  ALSO ATTACHED TO THE BOX WAS A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING BOX THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND: 1 METAL RECEPTACLE AT APPROXIMATELY 1.88 LITERS.  THIS RECEPTACLE HAD BEEN PLACED INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG.  THE INSPECTION FOUND NO ABSORBENT AND FOUND THAT THE WELD SEAM WAS BREACHED AT THE BOTTOM OF THE RECEPTACLE, LEAKING APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE.  THIS WAS A 2 PIECE SHIPMENT AND ONLY 1 PC WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE ACTION RESULTING IN THE SPILL IS UNKNOWN.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS AND ABSORBENT ADDED AND THEN FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

HERCULES' DRIVER WAS LOADING CRUDE OIL AT THE SECOND BAYOU FIELD AT HACKBERRY, LOUISIANA ON 12-01-99 @ 1:20 AM WHEN HE FELL ASLEEP AND OVERFILLED HIS TRANSPORT AND PUMPED APPROXIMATELY 40 BARRELS OF CRUDE OIL OUT THE HATCH ONTO THE GROUND SURFACE AREA.  THE OIL MIGRATED TO BOTH SIDES OF THE ROAD AND ENTERED THE WATER AREA UNDER THE ESTABLISHED TANK BATTERY.  UPON DISCOVERY OF THE SPILL, THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CEASED PUMPING.  THE DRIVER THEN IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE SPILL USING HIS MOBIL TELEPHONE TO HIS DISPATCH.  AFTER REPORTING THE SPILL, THE DRIVER PUMPED APPROXIMATELY 40 BARRELS OF CRUDE OIL BACK INTO THE TANK BATTERY.  USING THE METER AT THE LOCATION AND THE KNOWN CAPACITY OF THE CRUDE TRAILER, THE DRIVER ORIGINALLY ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 40 BARRELS WERE RELEASED; UPON FURTHER CALCULATIONS THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT APPROXIMATELY 20 BARRELS WERE RELEASED.  ACTION ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE, GILL ROWLAND, ASSUMED THE ROLE AS INCIDENT COMMANDER FOR HERCULES TRANSPORT AND ITS INSURANCE CARRIER KEMPER INSURANCE.  HE INSTRUCTED ME THAT HE WOULD DO ALL REGULATORY REPORTING AND THAT HE WOULD CALL OUT THE RESPONDERS AND MANAGE THE SPILL.  I RELAYED ALL TELEPHONE NUMBERS - JOE HENDERSON, GRIFF GORDON, DON SELF, GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL, ROY BAILEY CONSTRUCTION, AND HERCULES TRANSPORT TO GILL ROWLAND.  GILL THEN CALLED - LA STATE POLICE INCIDENT #996795 AND LOCAL LEPC INCIDENT #9-7251.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2:45 AM GILL CONFIRMED TO ME THAT HE HAD CALLED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL AND THEY HAD AGREED TO RESPOND.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0700 HOURS, 12-6-99, APRIA EMPLOYEE ROBERT COLLINS WAS MOVING A TRUCK AT THE APRIA BRANCH, 2909 EAST BROADWAY ROAD, PHOENIX, AZ WHEN HE CAUSED A OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID RELEASE. COLLINS HAD COMPLETED FILLING A HL119, 4L TANK MOUNTED IN A 1996 ISUZU TRUCK, AX LICENSE 5DF854 WITH 119 GALLONS OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIGUID.  HE WAS DISTRACTED FROM WHAT HE WAS DOING AND THEN PROCEEDED TO START TO MOVE THE TRUCK WITHOUT DISCONNECTING THE FILL HOSE.  THIS CAUSED THE PIPING ON THE 41 TANK TO BE PULLED LOOSE AND BROKEN OFF.  THIS ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO DRAIN ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD.  COLLINS IMMEDIATELY TURNED OFF THE IGNITION AND EXITED THE TRUCK.  HE PROCEEDED TO GET HELP FROM OTHER EMPLOYEES IN SECURING THE AREA FROM PEDESTRIAN AND VEHICLE TRAFFIC.  HE THEN CONTACTED THE BRANCH'S OXYGEN SUPPLIER WHO ADVISED HIM TO KEEP THE AREA SECURED AND TO LET THE OXYGEN EVAPORATE, WHICH THEY DID.  THERE WAS NO COLLATERAL DAMAGE AND NO INJURIES.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HOURS, 12-8-99, JORGE RUIZ, APRIA EMPLOYEE, WAS APPROACHING THE RAILROAD CROSSING ON LOS ANGELES AVE..SIMI VALLEY,  CA.  RUIZ LOOKED AWAY AND WHEN HE LOOKED UP THE FLASHING LIGHTS AT THE CROSSING WERE ON.  HE OVER REACTED, LOCKING UP THE BRAKES, LOOSING CONTROL OF THE TRUCK, A 1996 ISUZU, CA LICENSE 5B86596.  THE TRUCK PROCEEDED TO SLID SIDEWAYS AND TURN OVER ONTO HE PASSENGER SIDE.  LEONARDO DeFRANCO, DRIVING A NISSAN SENTRA, CA LICENSE 2XFW312, WAS IN THE NEXT LANE AND THE VEHICLES MADE CONTACT. SIMI VALLEY POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED.  ALTHOUGH THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF HAZMAT, BECAUSE THE TRUCK CONTAINED A PLACARDED AMOUNT OF OXYGEN, COMPRESSES AND REFRIGERATED LIQUID THE SCENE WAS SECURED AD TREATED AS A HAZMAT INCIDENT.  RUIZ RECEIVED CONTUSION TO HIS RIGHT ARM AND WAS TREATED AT THE SCENE.  DeFRANCO HAD SYMPTOMS OF A HEART ATTACK AND WAS TRANSPORTED BY PARAMEDICS TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL.  UPON ARRIVAL HE WAS FOUND TO BE UNINJURED AND RELEASED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON DECEMBER 4, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 2209 HOURS, APRIA EMPLOYEE MARK CUNNINGHAM WAS INVOLVED IN A SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  THE ACCIDENT WAS IN A CONSTRUCTION ZONE ON ROUTE 3,  JUST NORTH OF NEW POAG ROAD,  HARTFORD,  IL.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN THE VEHICLE, 1997 ISUZU TRUCK, LICENSE IL  37634H, HYDRAPLANED AND STRUCK A CONCRETE BARRIER.  THE IMPACT CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO TURN OVER ONTO ITS SIDE. THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING OXYGEN, COMPRESSED AND OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID.  IT WAS PLACARDED WITH THE YELLOW"OXYGEN 2" PLACARDS, WITH THE MANIFEST IN THE CAB.  THE HARTFORD  POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  ALTHOUGH THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF HAZMAT, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SECURED THE AREA AS SOON AS THEY SAW THE "OXYGEN 2"  PLACARDS ON THE TRUCK.  THEY PROCEEDED TO WORK THE SCENE AS A HAZMAT RELEASE.  ONCE THEY WERE SATISFIED THAT THERE WAS NO DANGER OF AN ACTUAL RELEASE THEY ALLOWED THE TRUCK TO BE RIGHTED AND REMOVED.  IN DOING  SO ROUTE 3  WAS CLOSED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS.  THERE WAS NO HAZMAT RELEASE, NO COLLATERAL DAMAGE AND NO INJURIES.

column168: THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF THE CARGO TANK.  BRENNER OIL COMPANY WAS MAKING A ROUTINE DELIVERY OF HEATING OIL TO THE RESIDENCE OF MATT BORDEAUX.  THE HOMEOWNERS WERE NOT AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FUEL DELIVERY.  THE HOME HAS TWO HEATING OIL TANKS - ONE OUTSIDE OF THE RESIDENCE (UNDERGROUND),  WHILE THE OTHER TANK IS LOCATED IN THE BASEMENT.  ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE HOUSE, THE HOMEOWNER MARKED WHICH TANK SHOULD BE FILLED.  HOWEVER, THE HOMEOWNER MARKED THE WRONG FILL PORT FOR DELIVERY, RESULTING IN FUEL OIL BEING DELIVERED TO THE TANK IN THE BASEMENT, WHICH WAS ALREADY PARTIALLY FULL AND HAD A LOOSE BUNG AT THE TOP.  LESS THAN 150 GALLONS WAS SPILLED FROM THE HEATING OIL TANK INTO THE BASEMENT.  MOST OF THE FUEL OIL WAS CONTAINED IN THE BASEMENT.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL OIL (ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN 25 GALLONS) FLOWED INTO THE BASEMENT'S SUMP PUMP, AT WHICH TIME IT WAS PUMPED OUTSIDE ONTO THE HOMEOWNER'S CONCRETE DRIVE.  AS SOON AS BRENNER WAS NOTIFIED BY THE HOMEOWNERS OF THIS PROBLEM, A SPILL RESPONSE COMPANY AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANT WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SITE.  THE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM PLACED ABSORBENT BOOMS AND OIL DRY IN THE BASEMENT AND ON THE CONCRETE DRIVE AND PROCEEDED WITH CLEANING UP THE RESULTANT DEBRIS INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS.  AFTER THE DEBRIS WAS REMOVED, THE BASEMENT AND CONCRETE DRIVE WERE WASHED AND SCRUBBED WITH A HIGH PRESSURE HOT WATER JET, WITH THE WASH LIQUIDS CAPTURED BY A VACUUM TRUCK.  SEVERAL INCHES OF TOPSOIL WERE REMOVED IN THE AREA WHERE FUEL OIL PONDED NEXT TO THE CONCRETE DRIVE.  ALL IMMEDIATE HAZARDS HAVE BEEN ABATED AT THIS SITE.

column168: WHILE AN EMPLOYEE WAS FILLING FORKLIFT CYLINDERS USING THE SAME PUMP THAT IS USED TO FILL THE BOBTAILS, THE BOBTAIL HOSE APPARENTLY VIBRATED LOOSE FROM THE HANGER WHERE IT WAS STORED AND STRUCK THE GROUND, PARTIALLY OPENING THE HAND WHEEL ON THE HOSE END VALVE. BOTH THE LIQUID ESV AND BALL VALVE AT THE BULKHEAD WERE INADVERTENTLY LEFT OPEN.  WITH THE PUMP RUNNING, THE EXCESSIVE PRESSURE BLEW THE HOSE END CAP OUT CAUSING A WHIPPING ACTION OF THE BOBTAIL HOSE AND DISCHARGE OF LIQUID TO THE ATMOSPHERE CREATING A VAPOR CLOUD.  IT APPEARS THAT A SPARK CAUSED FROM THE ROCKS BEING HIT BY THE HOSE END IGNITED THE VAPOR CLOUD. BULK PLANT OPERATING PROCEDURES ARE BEING REVIEWED BY ALL AFFECTED EMPLOYEES TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN. REPORT #515682

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY TOM DIPLEY, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR.  AGENT DIPLEY STATED HE HAD OBSERVED THE ABOVE TANK CAR LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE TANK CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CUT OF CARS BEING SWITCHED WAS FROM A BNSF INTERCHANGE THAT HAD ARRIVED THE PREVIOUS NIGHT.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE INSPECTED, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY  VENT, A STANDARD GATX TRI-VENT, MOUNTED ON TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE, WAS DISASSEMBLED, THE BURST DISC REMOVED, AND A LIKE TYPE BS&B 165 POUND STAINLESS/TEFLON DISC INSTALLED.  THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE EAST YARD MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT FOREMAN, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR.  DEVELOPED THE CARMEN WERE INSPECTING AN OUTBOUND (EASTBOUND) TRAIN IN YARD TRACK 204 AND OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM AREA OF THE ABOVE TANK CAR.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST LOS ANGELES YARD FACILITY AND LOCATED THE ABOVE TANK CAR MID POINT IN THE TRAIN.   INSPECTION DEVELOPED PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AT A RATE OF 2-3 DROPS PER MINUTE.  THE CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A BUTTERFLY VALVE, WHICH WAS NOT FULLY SEATED.  BY MOVING THE OPERATING HANDLE TO THE FULLY CLOSED POSITION AND THEN BACKING THE HANDLE TO SECURING PIN POSITION STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS ALSO LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND, WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO BYPASS AT THE THREADS.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS PROPERLY SECURED UTILIZING A PRESCRIBED WRENCH.  CONTACTED THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER,  SHELL, AND ADVISED THEM OF THE DISCREPANCY AND THEY W ILL HANDLE THE EXCEPTIONS WITH THEIR CUSTOMER.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE PHOENIX YARD. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ROGER GRANT, YARDMASTER, PHOENIX, WHO STATED THE TANK CAR WAS IN A SIDING AT THE WEST END OF THE YARD, AND NOTED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET BY AN INSPECTOR FROM THE STATE OF ARIZONA.  SINCE THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT THIS LOCATION, IT WAS LEFT IN PLACE.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED CALJET, THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE TO SEE IF THEY HAD SOMEONE FROM THEIR FACILITY THAT COULD INSPECT THE CAR.  THEY HAD NO ONE AVAILABLE.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH ERI, THE RAILROADS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR, REQUESTING A TEAM TO RESPOND AND MITIGATE THE LEAK.  UPON ERI'S ARRIVAL DEVELOPED THE CAR WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT A RATE OF 1 TO 2 DROPS PER MINUTE.  THIS CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH THE TOP OPERATING HANDLE FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AND UPON INSPECTION, DEVELOPED THE OPERATING ROD WAS LOOSE.  TWO FULL TURNS OF THE OPERATING HANDLE WERE REQUIRED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE BOTTOM OUTLET AND STOP THE LEAK.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE PACKING GLAND FOR THE OPERATING ROD WAS TIGHT, HOWEVER THE ROD TURNED FREELY, INDICATING THE PACKING MATERIAL WAS NOT TO STANDARD.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER AND LESSOR OF THE CAR, HIGH PLAINS, WHO WAS ADVISED THE PACKING GLAND MATERIAL AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET WOULD BE REPLACED.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES.

WHILE LOADING TRAILER AT SHIPPER'S, THE DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE ETERNAL VALVE.  THE DRIVER FIXED THE BAND CLAMP TO STOP THE LEAK.  SHIPPER PERSONNEL HANDLED THE CLEAN UP.  NO FURTHER INCIDENT.  NO INJURIES.
